<div type="translation">
<p>... Y.P.K. Ňörńę Jaya ParameŇõvaravarmadeva went out bearing on his head the order of Y.P.K. Ňörńę CampeŇõvara. He offered ... made good dams, cleaned the canals of Ňörńę VńęraCuk's rice-fields in this Ňöaka <supplied reason="subaudible">year</supplied> ..., <supplied reason="explanation">1</supplied> moon, <supplied reason="explanation">1</supplied> earth <supplied reason="explanation">i.e. in 11## Ňöaka</supplied>
                this rice-field <supplied reason="subaudible">is</supplied> a unit offered to Y.P.K. Svayamutpanna and Y.P.K. ŇörńępatńęŇõvara <supplied reason="subaudible">delimited</supplied> on the Eastern side by the ramp; on the Southern side <foreign>gnamŐÉŠł• pyńĀ</foreign> river by the rice-fields of the country; on the Southern side by P.L. IŇõńĀnavarman's rice-fields, the gods' rice-fields, the rice-fields <supplied reason="subaudible">constituting</supplied> the capital; on the Western side by the rice-fields near the edifices; on the Northern side by the great canal; three <foreign>atamŐÉ danrńĀk</foreign>; 500 <foreign>jńĀk</foreign> with <foreign>tandomŐÉ laŠĻÖguv</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">of</supplied> uneven <supplied reason="subaudible">lands</supplied>.</p>
</div>
<div type="translation" xml:lang="fra">
<p>... Y.P.K. Ňörńę Jaya ParameŇõvaravarmadeva sortit <supplied reason="subaudible">pour</supplied> aller diviser ... Y.P.K. Ňörńę CampeŇõvara. Il offrit ... fit de bons barrages, cura les canaux pour les rizi√®res de Ňörńę VńęraCuk en cette <supplied reason="subaudible">ann√©e</supplied> Ňöaka 11## <supplied reason="explanation">##, 1 <supplied reason="subaudible">lune</supplied>, 1 <supplied reason="subaudible">terre</supplied></supplied>
                  cette rizi√®re <supplied reason="subaudible">est</supplied> un emplacement offert √† Y.P.K. Svayamutpanna et Y.P.K. ŇörńępatńęŇõvara <supplied reason="subaudible">d√©limit√©e</supplied> du c√īt√© est par la d√©niv√©llation ; du c√īt√© sud <foreign>gnamŐÉŠł• pyńĀ</foreign> fleuve par les rizi√®res du pays ; du c√īt√© sud par les rizi√®res du P.L. IŇõńĀnavarman, les rizi√®res des dieux, les rizi√®res <supplied reason="subaudible">constituant</supplied> le capital ; du c√īt√© ouest par les rizi√®res pr√®s des √©difices ; du c√īt√© nord par le grand canal ; trois <foreign>atamŐÉ danrńĀk</foreign> ; 500 <foreign>jńĀk</foreign> avec <foreign>tandomŐÉ laŠĻÖguv</foreign> <supplied reason="subaudible">de terres</supplied> d√©nivel√©es.</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<!-- <p><bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:luce-1969-70"/>: <biblScope>8</biblScope></bibl> informs us that <quote>The oldest mentions of Pag√°n by name, curiously enough, are in two Cham inscription of Phan-Rang (PńĀŠĻáŠłćuraŠĻÖga), the P√ī-Nagar and the Lom-ng√∂ pillars, anterior to 1050 A.D. In the former the name is written <foreign>Pukam</foreign>, in the latter <foreign>PukńĀm</foreign></quote>. These two inscriptions are <ref target="C0030B2.xml">C. 30 B2</ref> (one of the inscriptions
               from Po Nagar at Nha Trang, which is still<foreign>in situ</foreign>) and C. 7. However, those two inscriptions are not endowed with the oldest mentions of the name of Pagan as there were engraved at the beginning of the 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> century, under the reign of Jaya ParameŇõvaravarman. About the wrong dating of these two inscriptions and the mention of Paganese in Cam inscriptions, see <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:ECIC-IV"/>: <check><biblScope>forthcoming</biblScope></check></bibl> and <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:griffiths-lepoutre-2013"/>: <check><biblScope>forthcoming</biblScope></check>.</bibl></p>
            <p>Concerning <foreign>ŇõvamŐÉl</foreign> (also occurred in <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00005.xml">C. 5</ref>), see the discussion in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:ECIC-IV"/>: <check><biblScope>forthcoming</biblScope></check></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Concerning <foreign>mauk</foreign> (also occurred in <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00005.xml">C. 5</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00006.xml">C. 6</ref>), see the discussion in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:ECIC-IV"/>: <check><biblScope>forthcoming</biblScope></check></bibl>.</p>
            <p>One could also find <foreign>pyńĀ</foreign> in <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00011.xml">C. 11</ref> A, l. 16 <foreign>vik pyńĀ</foreign>. <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:aymonier-1891"/>: <biblScope>72</biblScope></bibl> translated <foreign>vik pyńĀ</foreign> as <quote>une limite  partant (de)</quote> with a footnote saying that it is an hypothetical translation and that he could not link these two words with other modern words. In the present state of knowledge, we can not give any translation, see <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:ECIC-IV"/>: <check><biblScope>forthcoming</biblScope></check></bibl>.</p>
            <p>The words <foreign>atamŐÉ</foreign> and <foreign>danrńĀk</foreign> are recorded in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:AC-1906"/></bibl>, but without translation.</p>
            <p><foreign>mamŐÉ</foreign> is an epheretic form of <foreign>rumamŐÉ</foreign> also found in <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00030B4.xml">C. 30 B4</ref>.</p>
            <p>The word <foreign>truŠł•</foreign> (and its causative form <foreign>patruŠł•</foreign>, see <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00089.xml">C. 89</ref>) is linked to the malay word <foreign>terus</foreign>. It is an auxiliary verb expressing the accomplishment.</p>  --></div>
